The usecase is to use trait types to specify a schema

```Python
class Foo(HasTraits):
    bar = Dict(traits={
        'name': Unicode(required=True),
        'age': Int(),
        'preferences': Dict(traits={
            'language': Unicode('English'),
        }, required=True),
    })
```

It is not specific to widgets but my use cases are motivated by widgets. 

There might be other places where you would want to enforce a schema for a Dict attribute (such as the config system.)

I ran into this today adding a list parameter to a task. The current "append" syntax seems clunky to me. The cleanest way I've found to do it with argparse is to use ```nargs='+'```. ([Documentation for nargs](https://docs.python.org/3/library/argparse.html#nargs))

In interface.py, [ArgparseInterface.add_parameter](https://github.com/spotify/luigi/blob/master/luigi/interface.py#L253), this would look something like:
```python
@classmethod
def add_parameter(cls, parser, param_name, param, prefix=None):
    description = []
    if prefix:
        description.append('%s.%s' % (prefix, param_name))
    else:
        description.append(param_name)
    if param.description:
        description.append(param.description)
    if param.has_value:
        description.append(" [default: %s]" % (param.value,))

    if param.is_list:
        parser.add_argument('--' + param_name.replace('_', '-'), help=' '.join(description), default=None, nargs='+')
    else:
        if param.is_boolean:
            action = "store_true"
        else:
            action = "store"
        parser.add_argument('--' + param_name.replace('_', '-'), help=' '.join(description), default=None, action=action)
```

We could handle conditional dependencies using [environment markers][1].  It's basically like this:

```python
setup(
    ...,
    extras_requires={
        ":python_version<'3.0'": ['pytz'],
    }
)
```

[1]: https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0508/#environment-markers

