@madhav5589 Disclaimer: I don't know much about WinPE, and as far as I know it's an untested scenario.

> I was using <OutputType>Exe</OutputType> in the project file with RunTimeIdentifier as "Any".

If you are using a self-contained deployment (which I think makes sense in this case), then you need to choose a specific, concrete RID. In this case, I would try "win7-x64". The output of this should include coreclr.dll, "myapp.dll", and "myapp.exe", as well as a bunch of other miscellaneous files.

@lynxionxs I made the session store replaceable in #32 and released v1.14.0 to PyPI which includes this change.

[Here's an example](https://github.com/aichaos/rivescript-python/tree/master/eg/sessions) that uses Redis as the session store. You'll need to write your own to use a database.

At some point in the future I'll make some "more official" modules for popular storage back-ends (Redis, SQLAlchemy for SQLite/MySQL/Postgres) and either release those separately on PyPI or bundle them in the RiveScript module itself (like `from rivescript.sessions.redis import RedisSessionStorage`); haven't decided yet.

A warning to the logger is good, but we should also output something to the state log. That way we can tell people to look at path.events to see if anything out of the ordinary happened.

@salls, since you're dealing with other SimProcedure related weirdness, it might be good to log those as well.

And finally, if we actually start using the event log for useful things, we should probably split the actions out of it (at least filter them out during iteration); otherwise, people will get overwhelmed with the actions.

