This feels like a gcc bug related to `auto` return types to me.  It doesn't appear to be specific to `py::overload_cast`: gcc won't even accept a regular member function cast there:

```C++
template <typename T>
class C {
    T x;
public:
    auto &f() { return x; }
    const auto &f() const { return x; }
};

int main() {
    (void) (double & (C<double>::*)()) &C<double>::f;
}
```
fails to compile under g++, works under clang.

I've no idea of how one could work around the issue.

